# Understanding <C81> Through Code

The relationship between <C81> and <B81> is best understood through implementation. Here's how they work together:

```python
def <B81>(x):
    return constant_value

def <C81>(x):
    return <B81>(x)
```

When you call <C81> with any argument, it immediately delegates to <B81> and returns that result unchanged. The wrapper <C81> adds a layer of indirection but maintains identical output behavior to <B81>. Whether you invoke <C81> or <B81> directly, the returned value will always be the same, demonstrating that <C81> is a pure delegation wrapper around its base function <B81>.

# Understanding <C56> Through Code

The relationship between <C56> and <B56> is best understood through implementation. <B56> serves as the base constant function, while <C56> wraps it:

```python
def <B56>(x):
    return CONSTANT_VALUE

def <C56>(x):
    return <B56>(x)
```

When you call <C56> with any argument, it immediately delegates to <B56> and returns whatever <B56> returns. Since <B56> is a constant function, <C56> inherits this property. Whether you invoke <C56> with positive numbers, negative numbers, or zero, the return value is always identical to what <B56> would produce. The wrapper pattern here creates a second interface to the same underlying constant behavior, with no intermediate processing or value modification occurring between the two function layers.
